Fairmaire
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[212,1172,1040,1224]" pageId="10" pageNumber="587">
All of the known species are distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[720,792,1040,1064]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="587">China</collectingCountry>
, where they are restricted to the south-western area (
<figureCitation box="[440,538,1072,1096]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[212,279,824,846]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,175,794]" captionTargetId="figure-232@10.[212,1173,173,794]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Distribution of Cyrebion Fairmaire. Different localities of the three species are: • Cyrebion laticornis Fairmaire, Δ Cyrebion subrufolineatus (Wittmer) comb. nov. - Cyrebion gracilicornis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5207762" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5207762/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="587">Figure 3</figureCitation>
). Judging from the current distribution pattern, we suppose that this genus may not be endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[727,799,1104,1128]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="587">China</collectingCountry>
, instead, more unknown species should exist within the Oriental region, especially in the adjacent area of south-west 
<collectingCountry box="[212,285,1168,1192]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="587">China</collectingCountry>
. We hope that this study will initiate the recognition of this genus, with more and more species discovered by extensive investigations in future.
</paragraph>
